Let (S \triangleright P, \iota ^S, \sigma ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleright Q, \iota ^T, \sigma ^T, \text {pr}^T) be monad containers. A distributive law of S \triangleright P over T \triangleright Q is given by the data:
\begin {align*} &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to T) \to T \\ &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to S \\ &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to P\ s \\ &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\ \end {align*}
where the following equalities hold:
\begin {align*} u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda \_ . \iota ^S)\\ u\ s\ (\lambda \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda \_. s)\\ v\ \{\iota ^S\}\ \{\lambda \_. t\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda \_. \iota ^T\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ \\ u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\\ u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S)\ q &= \sigma ^S\ (u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q)\ (\lambda p . u_2\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (g\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (v_2\ q\ p))\\ \text {pr}^S_1\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\\ \text {pr}^S_2\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ v_2\ q\ p &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ \\ u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f)\ (\lambda q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p)))\\ u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p))\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\ v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}^T_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}^T_2\ (v_2\ q\ p) \end {align*}
We use the notation \langle f , g \rangle := \lambda x . (f\ x , g\ x), with some implicit use of currying and uncurrying where this shorthand is utilised.
u is defined as \langle u_1 , u_2 \rangle and v is defined as \langle v_1 , v_2 \rangle .

Given a monad container (S \triangleright  P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}), it's extension (see container extension) is the monad (\lbrack \negthinspace \lbrack  S \triangleright  P \rbrack \negthinspace \rbrack , \eta , \mu ) on \mathbf {Set} where

       \begin {align*}            \eta _A\ a &:= (\iota , \lambda  \_ . a)\\     \mu _A\ (s , f) &:= (\sigma \ s\ (\lambda  p . \pi _1\ (f\ p)) , \lambda  p' . \pi _2\ (f\ (\text {pr}_1\ p'))\ (\text {pr}_2\ p'))        \end {align*}   

  The diagrams for \eta  and \mu  commute given the equations of a monad container.

Let (S \triangleright P, \iota ^S, \sigma ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleright Q, \iota ^T, \sigma ^T, \text {pr}^T) be monad containers. A distributive law of S \triangleright P over T \triangleright Q is given by the data:
\begin {align*} &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to T) \to T \\ &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to S \\ &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to P\ s \\ &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\ \end {align*}
where the following equalities hold:
\begin {align*} u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda \_ . \iota ^S)\\ u\ s\ (\lambda \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda \_. s)\\ v\ \{\iota ^S\}\ \{\lambda \_. t\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda \_. \iota ^T\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ \\ u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\\ u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S)\ q &= \sigma ^S\ (u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q)\ (\lambda p . u_2\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (g\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (v_2\ q\ p))\\ \text {pr}^S_1\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\\ \text {pr}^S_2\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ v_2\ q\ p &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ \\ u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f)\ (\lambda q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p)))\\ u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p))\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\ v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}^T_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}^T_2\ (v_2\ q\ p) \end {align*}
We use the notation \langle f , g \rangle := \lambda x . (f\ x , g\ x), with some implicit use of currying and uncurrying where this shorthand is utilised.
u is defined as \langle u_1 , u_2 \rangle and v is defined as \langle v_1 , v_2 \rangle .

Let S \triangleright  P be a container. A monad container (or mnd-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleright  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &: S\\       \sigma  &: \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  S) \to  S\\       \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  S\}} P\ (\sigma \ s\ f) \to  \sum _{p : P\ s} P\ (f\ p)     \end {align*}   
  For which the following laws hold:
       \begin {align*}       \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota  ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ \iota \ (\lambda  \_ . a ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ (\sigma \ a\ f)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)) &= \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  p . \sigma \ (f\ p)\ (g\ p))\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \sigma  above them.
